1) Where pricing should live in the page flow

Place Pricing after “Dlaczego Autoceny?” and before FAQ / final CTA.

Reason: user already understands how it works + why it matters, now they’re ready to ask “ok, how much?”

2) Section layout: keep the two-sided structure

Use the same visual language you already have:

Title: “Cennik” or “Plany”

Subtitle (short): “Dla kierowców i warsztatów”

Two columns/cards:

Left: Kierowcy

Right: Warsztaty

Keep the KIEROWCA / WARSZTAT pills you used in “Jak to działa”.

Compact rule

Everything must fit without scrolling inside cards on desktop.

3) Driver pricing: strong but not intrusive
Primary message

Driver side should visually communicate: “Start for free”.

Card structure (Kierowcy)

Header: “Kierowcy”

Big label: “Darmowy plan”

One sentence: “Wystarczy do sprawdzenia Autoceny.”

Then a compact “Limits” block (3 rows max):

Otwarte zlecenia: X

Zlecenia / dzień: Y

Pytania / zlecenie: Z

Don’t show numbers as tiny footnotes — make them scannable.

Paid plan (driver)

Show as “Plus” or “Premium” (whatever you choose), but keep it soft:

Header: “Plan Premium”

2–3 bullets max, focused on outcomes:

“Więcej otwartych zleceń”

“Więcej zleceń dziennie”

“Więcej pytań / szybsze doprecyzowanie”

Small price placeholder is ok, but don’t make it the hero.

CTA: “Zobacz Premium” (secondary) rather than “Buy now”.

UX tone
This is not a SaaS upsell page. It’s a marketplace. Keep it calm.

4) Shop pricing: subscription, clear and confident

Workshops need a subscription to participate. Make it explicit but not aggressive.

Card structure (Warsztaty)

Header: “Warsztaty”

Big label: “Subskrypcja”

One sentence: “Dostajesz zlecenia z okolicy i możesz wysyłać wyceny.”

Then 2 pricing toggles:

Monthly / Annual switch (annual shows “save X%” badge)

Plan card: one plan is enough for MVP:

“Warsztat” (or “Basic”)

Bullet points (max 3):

“Zlecenia w Twoim promieniu”

“Pytania + wyceny w aplikacji”

“Konkurujesz lokalnie wartością”

CTA: “Dołącz jako warsztat” (primary on shop side)

Important
Workshops will ask “how many leads?” Don’t promise. Add a short neutral line:

“Liczba zleceń zależy od Twojej okolicy i popytu.”

5) Visual hierarchy (so it feels “strong”)

Use the teal as the driver accent (consistent with the rest).

Use the gold/amber accent you already use for workshop-side elements.

Make “Free” visually obvious (badge “Darmowy”).

Make “Annual” look like the smart choice (small “Oszczędzasz …” pill), but don’t overdo.

6) Keep it non-intrusive: no popups, no sticky pricing bar

No modal pricing popups.

No “discount countdown”.

No interrupting scroll.
This should read as “transparent pricing”, not a sales funnel.

7) Microcopy guidance (Polish)

Use simple labels; avoid SaaS jargon.

Driver

“Darmowy plan”

“Limit otwartych zleceń”

“Limit zleceń dziennie”

“Limit pytań na zlecenie”

Shop

“Subskrypcja warsztatu”

“Miesięcznie / Rocznie”

“Dołącz jako warsztat”